The Geolocation API allows websites to ask for and receive a user's physical location (with their permission). This powers features like "find stores near me," weather websites, ride-sharing apps, and local search results.

**Important privacy note:** Browsers always ask for permission first. Users can deny location access, and your code must handle that gracefully.

**How geolocation works:**
```javascript
// Check if browser supports geolocation
if (navigator.geolocation) {
  navigator.geolocation.getCurrentPosition(showPosition, showError);
} else {
  console.log("Geolocation is not supported by this browser.");
}

// Success function - runs when user allows location
function showPosition(position) {
  const latitude = position.coords.latitude;
  const longitude = position.coords.longitude;
  console.log(`Latitude: ${latitude}, Longitude: ${longitude}`);
  document.getElementById("location").innerHTML = 
    `You are at: ${latitude.toFixed(4)}, ${longitude.toFixed(4)}`;
}

// Error function - runs when user denies or something fails
function showError(error) {
  switch(error.code) {
    case error.PERMISSION_DENIED:
      console.log("User denied the request for location.");
      break;
    case error.POSITION_UNAVAILABLE:
      console.log("Location information is unavailable.");
      break;
    case error.TIMEOUT:
      console.log("The request to get user location timed out.");
      break;
  }
}
```

**Complete HTML example with a button:**
```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <title>Geolocation Example</title>
</head>
<body>
  <h1>Find My Location</h1>
  <button onclick="getLocation()">Where am I?</button>
  <p id="output"></p>

  <script>
    function getLocation() {
      const output = document.getElementById("output");

      if (!navigator.geolocation) {
        output.innerHTML = "Geolocation is not supported by your browser.";
        return;
      }

      output.innerHTML = "Requesting location...";

      navigator.geolocation.getCurrentPosition(
        (position) => {
          const lat = position.coords.latitude;
          const lon = position.coords.longitude;
          output.innerHTML = `Your coordinates: ${lat.toFixed(6)}, ${lon.toFixed(6)}`;

          // Optional: Show on Google Maps
          const mapsUrl = `https://www.google.com/maps?q=${lat},${lon}`;
          output.innerHTML += `<br><a href="${mapsUrl}" target="_blank">View on Google Maps →</a>`;
        },
        (error) => {
          if (error.code === 1) {
            output.innerHTML = "You denied location access. Please allow and try again.";
          } else {
            output.innerHTML = "Error getting location: " + error.message;
          }
        }
      );
    }
  </script>
</body>
</html>
```

**Real-time location tracking (watchPosition):**
```javascript
// Updates continuously as the user moves (for navigation apps)
const watchId = navigator.geolocation.watchPosition((position) => {
  console.log("New position:", position.coords.latitude, position.coords.longitude);
});

// Stop tracking when done
navigator.geolocation.clearWatch(watchId);
```

**Accuracy levels:** GPS on phones (accurate to ~5 meters), WiFi (20-50 meters), IP address (city-level, ~50km). Mobile devices are most accurate.

**Common use cases:** Local weather, store locators, ride-hailing (Uber/Lyft), fitness tracking maps, delivery tracking (DoorDash/Foodora), social media check-ins.

The HTML5 Drag and Drop API lets users click, drag, and drop elements anywhere on a page — no complex JavaScript libraries required. This powers features like file uploads, task boards (Trello), and customizable layouts.

**The four essential steps for drag and drop:**

**Step 1: Make an element draggable**
```html
<div id="drag1" draggable="true">Drag me!</div>
```
The `draggable="true"` attribute is all you need to make an element movable.

**Step 2: Define what happens when dragging starts**
```javascript
document.getElementById("drag1").addEventListener("dragstart", function(event) {
  event.dataTransfer.setData("Text", event.target.id);
});
```
This stores the dragged element's ID so the drop target knows what was dragged.

**Step 3: Allow dropping on a target**
By default, elements cannot be dropped onto other elements. You must prevent the default behavior:
```javascript
document.getElementById("dropzone").addEventListener("dragover", function(event) {
  event.preventDefault(); // Required for drop to work
});
```

**Step 4: Define the drop action**
```javascript
document.getElementById("dropzone").addEventListener("drop", function(event) {
  event.preventDefault();
  const data = event.dataTransfer.getData("Text");
  const draggedElement = document.getElementById(data);
  event.target.appendChild(draggedElement);
});
```

**Complete working example:**
```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <title>Drag and Drop Example</title>
  <style>
    .draggable {
      width: 100px;
      height: 100px;
      background: lightblue;
      margin: 10px;
      padding: 10px;
      cursor: grab;
    }
    .dropzone {
      width: 300px;
      min-height: 200px;
      border: 2px dashed gray;
      margin-top: 20px;
      padding: 10px;
    }
  </style>
</head>
<body>
  <h1>Drag and Drop Demo</h1>

  <div id="drag1" class="draggable" draggable="true">Item 1</div>
  <div id="drag2" class="draggable" draggable="true">Item 2</div>
  <div id="drag3" class="draggable" draggable="true">Item 3</div>

  <div id="dropzone" class="dropzone">
    Drop items here
  </div>

  <script>
    const draggables = document.querySelectorAll(".draggable");
    const dropzone = document.getElementById("dropzone");

    // Make all draggable items store their ID when drag starts
    draggables.forEach(item => {
      item.addEventListener("dragstart", function(event) {
        event.dataTransfer.setData("text/plain", event.target.id);
        event.target.style.opacity = "0.5";
      });

      item.addEventListener("dragend", function(event) {
        event.target.style.opacity = "1";
      });
    });

    // Allow drop on dropzone
    dropzone.addEventListener("dragover", function(event) {
      event.preventDefault();
    });

    // Handle the actual drop
    dropzone.addEventListener("drop", function(event) {
      event.preventDefault();
      const id = event.dataTransfer.getData("text/plain");
      const draggedElement = document.getElementById(id);
      dropzone.appendChild(draggedElement);
    });
  </script>
</body>
</html>
```

**Drag and drop for file uploads:**
```javascript
const dropzone = document.getElementById("upload-area");

dropzone.addEventListener("drop", function(event) {
  event.preventDefault();
  const files = event.dataTransfer.files; // Array of dropped files

  for (let i = 0; i < files.length; i++) {
    console.log("File:", files[i].name, files[i].size, "bytes");
    // Upload the file via AJAX/Fetch here
  }
});
```

**Limitations:** Drag and drop works inconsistently across complex nested elements. For professional apps, many developers use JavaScript libraries (like SortableJS) that provide smoother behavior.

HTML5 introduced two simple ways to store data directly in the user's browser: localStorage (persistent) and sessionStorage (temporary). This allows websites to remember user preferences, save draft forms, or store shopping cart items without a server database.

**localStorage vs sessionStorage:**
| Feature | localStorage | sessionStorage |
|---------|--------------|----------------|
| Persistence | Forever (until manually cleared) | Until browser tab is closed |
| Scope | Across all tabs/windows | Only within the same tab |
| Maximum size | ~5-10MB per domain | ~5-10MB per domain |
| Best for | User preferences, theme settings, saved items | Form drafts, step-by-step wizard data |

**Basic operations (same syntax for both):**
```javascript
// Store data
localStorage.setItem("username", "JohnDoe");
localStorage.setItem("theme", "dark");

// Retrieve data
const username = localStorage.getItem("username");
console.log(username); // "JohnDoe"

// Remove a specific item
localStorage.removeItem("theme");

// Clear all data for this domain
localStorage.clear();

// Check how many items stored
const itemCount = localStorage.length;
console.log(itemCount);
```

**Storing objects and arrays:**
localStorage only stores strings. To save objects, use JSON.stringify() and JSON.parse():
```javascript
// Saving an object
const userSettings = {
  name: "Alice",
  volume: 75,
  notifications: true
};
localStorage.setItem("settings", JSON.stringify(userSettings));

// Retrieving the object
const savedSettings = JSON.parse(localStorage.getItem("settings"));
console.log(savedSettings.name); // "Alice"
```

**Complete example: Theme switcher with localStorage**
```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <title>Theme Switcher with localStorage</title>
  <style>
    body.dark {
      background: #1a1a2e;
      color: #eee;
    }
    body.light {
      background: #f0f0f0;
      color: #333;
    }
    button {
      padding: 10px 20px;
      margin: 10px;
      cursor: pointer;
    }
  </style>
</head>
<body>
  <h1>My Website</h1>
  <button id="darkBtn">Dark Mode</button>
  <button id="lightBtn">Light Mode</button>
  <p>Your theme preference is saved even after you close the browser!</p>

  <script>
    // Load saved theme on page load
    const savedTheme = localStorage.getItem("theme");
    if (savedTheme) {
      document.body.className = savedTheme;
    } else {
      document.body.className = "light"; // Default
    }

    // Save and apply dark mode
    document.getElementById("darkBtn").addEventListener("click", () => {
      document.body.className = "dark";
      localStorage.setItem("theme", "dark");
    });

    // Save and apply light mode
    document.getElementById("lightBtn").addEventListener("click", () => {
      document.body.className = "light";
      localStorage.setItem("theme", "light");
    });
  </script>
</body>
</html>
```

**Complete example: Shopping cart with sessionStorage**
```javascript
// Add item to cart (session-only, clears when tab closes)
function addToCart(productId, productName, price) {
  let cart = sessionStorage.getItem("cart");

  if (!cart) {
    cart = [];
  } else {
    cart = JSON.parse(cart);
  }

  cart.push({ id: productId, name: productName, price: price });
  sessionStorage.setItem("cart", JSON.stringify(cart));
  console.log(`${productName} added to cart`);
}

// Display cart items
function showCart() {
  const cart = JSON.parse(sessionStorage.getItem("cart") || "[]");
  console.log(`Cart has ${cart.length} items:`);
  cart.forEach(item => console.log(`- ${item.name}: $${item.price}`));
}
```

**Important limitations:**
- Storage is per domain — `https://example.com` cannot access `https://another-site.com` data.
- Data is not encrypted — never store passwords, credit cards, or personal IDs.
- Users can clear storage at any time — never rely on it for critical data.
- Storage is synchronous — large amounts of data can slow down your page.

**When localStorage is perfect for:** User preferences (theme, language, font size), game save states, reading progress on articles, recently viewed items, form auto-save drafts.

**When NOT to use localStorage:** Authentication tokens (use HTTP-only cookies instead), sensitive data (no encryption), large files (>5MB), data that must sync across devices (use a server database).

Before smartphones, every website was designed for desktop screens. When the iPhone launched in 2007, it tried to fit full desktop websites onto a tiny 320px screen by zooming out. That made everything tiny and unreadable. The meta viewport tag fixed this by telling mobile browsers: "Scale my page properly for this screen size."

**The magic tag (always include it):**
```html
<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
```

**What each part does:**
- `width=device-width` — Sets the page width to match the device's screen width (not zoomed-out desktop width).
- `initial-scale=1.0` — Sets the initial zoom level to 100% (not zoomed out or in).

**Without this tag (bad):**
```html
<!-- Browsers assume 980px desktop width on a 375px phone → everything is tiny -->
```
User sees: An entire desktop website squished into a small phone screen. Text is unreadable, buttons are tiny. The user must pinch and zoom constantly.

**With this tag (good):**
```html
<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
```
User sees: Content that fills the phone screen. Text is readable, buttons are tappable. No pinching needed.

**Additional viewport settings:**
```html
<!-- Prevent zooming (usually NOT recommended - hurts accessibility) -->
<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0, user-scalable=no">

<!-- Set maximum zoom level -->
<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0, maximum-scale=2.0">
```
**Warning:** Avoid `user-scalable=no` unless you have a very good reason. It blocks users with visual impairments from zooming your page.

**How viewport works with CSS media queries:**
The viewport tag enables CSS media queries to work correctly. Media queries apply different styles based on screen width.

```css
/* Default: desktop styles */
.container {
  display: flex;
  gap: 20px;
}

/* Tablet screens (768px to 1024px) */
@media (max-width: 1024px) {
  .container {
    gap: 15px;
  }
}

/* Mobile screens (below 768px) */
@media (max-width: 768px) {
  .container {
    flex-direction: column; /* Stack vertically on phones */
    gap: 10px;
  }
}
```

**Testing responsive design:**
1. In Chrome: Right-click → Inspect → Click the "Toggle device toolbar" icon (phone/tablet icon).
2. Select different devices (iPhone, Pixel, iPad) from the dropdown.
3. Resize your browser window manually to see how the layout changes.

**Common responsive patterns:**
- **Stacking:** Columns stack vertically on mobile instead of sitting side-by-side.
- **Hamburger menu:** Navigation links hide behind a ☰ icon on mobile.
- **Larger touch targets:** Buttons are at least 44x44px on mobile for fingers.
- **Readable font sizes:** Minimum 16px for body text on mobile.

**Complete responsive example:**
```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
  <title>Responsive Page</title>
  <style>
    body {
      font-family: system-ui, sans-serif;
      margin: 0;
      padding: 20px;
    }
    .cards {
      display: flex;
      gap: 20px;
      flex-wrap: wrap;
    }
    .card {
      background: #f5f5f5;
      padding: 20px;
      border-radius: 8px;
      flex: 1;
      min-width: 200px;
    }
    /* Mobile: cards stack, font gets smaller */
    @media (max-width: 640px) {
      body {
        padding: 10px;
      }
      .cards {
        flex-direction: column;
      }
      h1 {
        font-size: 1.5rem;
      }
    }
  </style>
</head>
<body>
  <h1>Responsive Card Layout</h1>
  <div class="cards">
    <div class="card">Card 1</div>
    <div class="card">Card 2</div>
    <div class="card">Card 3</div>
  </div>
</body>
</html>
```

Remember: Adding the meta viewport tag is the single most important step for mobile-friendly websites. Without it, even the most beautiful responsive CSS will not work correctly on phones.
